 public attention to the dreams eventually became too much for the Spanish king. Stung that Lucrecia had accurately foreseen the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588, Philip II ordered the Inquisition to arrest her on charges of heresy and sedition. During Lucrecia's imprisonment, trial, and torture, the carefully collected records of her dreams were preserved and analyzed by the court. The authenticity of these dreams, and their potentially explosive significance, became the focal point of the Church's investigation. Returning to these records of a dreamer from another era, Lucrecia the Dreamer is the first book to examine Lucrecia's dreams as dreams, as accurate reports of psychological experiences with roots in the brain's natural cycles of activity during sleep. Using methods from the cognitive science of religion, dream researcher Kelly Bulkeley finds meaningful patterns in Lucrecia's dreaming prophecies and sheds new light on the infinitely puzzling question at the center of her trial, a question that has vexed all religious traditions throughout history: How can we determine if a dream is, or is not, a true revelation?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCognitive science. 0aDreamsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aFortune-telling by dreamszSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aInquisitionzSpain. 0aPsychology, Religious. 0aWomen prophetszSpainvBiography. 4aLucrecia de Leon. 4aSpanish Inquisition. 4acognitive science. 4adream research. 4adreams. 4aprophetic dreaming. 7aRELIGION / Psychology of Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360448340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604483423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604483.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Compl